Best wishes to everyone on the fifth day of Navratri. Skandamata is worshiped on the fifth day of Navratri. Maa #Skandamata‚Äã is the fifth incarnation of Goddess Durga. The word Skandmata is made up of two words - Skanda and Mata. Skanda is another name for Lord Kartikeya, Kartikeya is the son of Bholenath and Parvati mother and brother of Ganesha. Mata means mother and thus Skandamata means mother of Kartikeya. Hence Skandamata is a form of Maa Parvati.
Goddess Durga has four arms in the form of Skandamata. She is holding Kartikeya (Skanda) in one hand, holds a lotus in the other and third hand and blesses the devotees with the fourth hand. She rides a lion and sits on a lotus, which is why she is also called Padmasana. Karthikeya is known as Murugan in South India. He is the commander-in-chief of the army of gods.  Worshiping Maa Skandamata awakens the Vishuddhi Chakra, through which effect one attains the attainment of speech, increases in age and becomes a scholar. The worship of Skandmata leads to the knowledge of sixteen arts and sixteen figures. There is an interesting story of the birth of Karthikeya.Let us now hear the story of Mother Skanda Mata and know that the puja vidhi of Mother Skanda Mata. The story of Skanda Mata reveals who the Goddess Skanda Mata is. How did the goddess get this name of Skanda Mata?
